docs.abstract: Copwatch teaches Australia’s Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples how to use their mobile phones’ cameras to battle police brutality.
docs.snippet: Copwatch teaches Australia’s Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples how to use their mobile phones’ cameras to battle police brutality.
docs.lead_paragraph: PERTH, Australia — In one video, a black prisoner screams “I can’t breathe” 12 times as he is pinned down by a group of guards. In another, a police car swerves to run down a black teenager. As the young man has a seizure in the street, the officers handcuff him rather than offer first aid.

headline.main: Indigenous Australians Use Tech to Expose Police Abuse

docs.lead_paragraph: Our nonfiction recommendations this week take you from medieval manuscripts to Covid-era domestic arrangements; and from the birth of American transcendentalism in Concord, Mass., to the death of a latter-day American transcendentalist in the Parvati Valley of northern India. We also recommend a book that explores English’s role as the world’s dominant language and, in fiction, new novels by Julie Otsuka, Sarah Manguso, Paul Vidich and more. Happy reading.

docs.abstract: In the last installment in his 12-play series, Richard Nelson asks how his characters, and the theater, got where they are today.
docs.snippet: In the last installment in his 12-play series, Richard Nelson asks how his characters, and the theater, got where they are today.
docs.lead_paragraph: Kate, a woman in her late 60s, sits alone at a weather-beaten table, the clutter of a cauliflower lasagna mostly cleared and her dinner companions now out for the evening. Together, they have spent most of the last two hours talking about Rose, Kate’s wife, who six months earlier, while dying of ovarian cancer, was killed by Covid-19 instead.

headline.main: Review: In ‘What Happened?,’ a Questioning Farewell to Rhinebeck

docs.abstract: In a year that offered glimmers of hope across the world of arts, these performers and creators rose to the occasion.
docs.snippet: In a year that offered glimmers of hope across the world of arts, these performers and creators rose to the occasion.
docs.lead_paragraph: The cultural world began to sputter back to life this year, and in turn, so did many of us — slipping out of our sweats and into movie theaters, clubs and Broadway shows. Even for those who were less confident rubbing (or bumping) elbows in public, artists brought us plenty of joy in the safety of our home. It may not have been the beforetimes, but in 2021, these artists and creators from across the arts gave us a fresh outlook.

headline.print_headline: Breakout Artists Who Enriched the Year
